  <li>
    <p>One of the most useful tools was the After-Action Review, the truth-telling session. AARs happen immediately after each mission and consist of a short meeting in which the team gathers to discuss and replay key decisions. AARs are led not by commanders but by enlisted men. There are no agendas, and no minutes are kept. The goal is to create a flat landscape without rank, where people can figure out what really happened and talk about mistakesâ€”especially their own.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Good AARs follow a template. â€œYou have to do it right away,â€ Cooper says. â€œYou put down your gun, circle up, and start talking. Usually you take the mission from beginning to end, chronologically. You talk about every decision, and you talk about the process. You have to resist the temptation to wrap it all up in a bow, and try to dig for the truth of what happened, so people can really learn from it. You have to ask why, and then when they respond, you ask another why. Why did you shoot at that particular point? What did you see? How did you know? What other options were there? You ask and ask and ask.â€
The goal of an AAR is not to excavate truth for truthâ€™s sake, or to assign credit and blame, but rather to build a shared mental model that can be applied to future missions. â€œLook, nobody can see it all or know it all,â€ Cooper says. â€œBut if you keep getting together and digging out what happened, then after a while everybody can see whatâ€™s really happening, not just their small piece of it. People can share experiences and mistakes. They can see how what they do affects others, and we can start to create a group mind where everybody can work together and perform to the teamâ€™s potential.â€</p>
