  <li>
    <p>Marci invented a method in which he videoed conversations while tracking galvanic skin responseâ€”the change in electrical resistance that measures emotional arousal. He discovered that for much of the time, the arousal curves of two people in conversation bore little or no relation to each other. But he also found special moments, in certain conversations, when the two curves fell into perfect sync. Marci called these moments concordances. â€œConcordances happen when one person can react in an authentic way to the emotion being projected in the room,â€ Marci says. â€œItâ€™s about understanding in an empathic way, then doing something in terms of gesture, comment, or expression that creates a connection.â€</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The most important moments in conversation happen when one person is actively, intently listening. â€œItâ€™s not an accident that concordance happens when thereâ€™s one person talking and the other person listening,â€ Marci says. â€œItâ€™s very hard to be empathic when youâ€™re talking. Talking is really complicated, because youâ€™re thinking and planning what youâ€™re going to say, and you tend to get stuck in your own head. But not when youâ€™re listening. When youâ€™re really listening, you lose time. Thereâ€™s no sense of yourself, because itâ€™s not about you. Itâ€™s all about this taskâ€”to connect completely to that person.â€</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Marci has connected increases in concordances to increases in perceived empathy: the more concordances occur, the closer the two people feel. Whatâ€™s more, the changes in closeness happen not gradually but all at once. â€œThereâ€™s often one moment where it happens,â€ he says. â€œThereâ€™s an accelerated change to the relationship that happens when youâ€™re able to really listen, to be incredibly present with the person. Itâ€™s like a breakthroughâ€”â€˜We were like this, but now weâ€™re going to interact in a new way, and we both understand that itâ€™s happened.â€™â€</p>
